<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="208" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1577,1782]" pageId="7" pageNumber="208">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[204,271,1577,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Dasyhelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grisea">grisea</taxonomicName>
group is equivalent to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Dominiak 2012" authorityName="Dominiak" authorityYear="2012" box="[702,1031,1577,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Dasyhelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[702,820,1577,1601]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="208">Dasyhelea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dominiak" box="[838,1023,1577,1602]" pageId="7" pageNumber="208" refString="Dominiak, P. (2012) Biting midges of the genus Dasyhelea Kieffer (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) in Poland. Polish Journal of Entomology, 81, 211 - 304." type="journal article" year="2012">Dominiak 2012</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Species are distinguished from all other groups/subgenera of 
<taxonomicName box="[461,579,1613,1637]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Dasyhelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[461,579,1613,1637]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="208">Dasyhelea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by their broad elliptical, bilobate or heart-shaped frontal sclerite, heavily sculptured antennal flagellomeres and elongate flagellomere 13 with tapered slender apex. Male tergite 9 usually with long apicolateral processes; sternite 9 relatively short with posterior margin concave, straight or convex; gonocoxal apodemes and paramere forming an asymmetrical structure; gonocoxite often with mesal hook or tubercle. Female subgenital plate usually with triangular, arrowhead-shaped or slender distal portion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
